&gt; My question was whether "net.umn.edu" was a reasonable sub-domain
&gt; name.  The answer is no.  Several people pointed out a real problem:
&gt; name translation into and out of the U.K.  In particular, mailers
&gt; would tend to try to look up the name "edu.umn.net" and not succeed.

We have used the hostname "net.bio.net" for a mail host, including
hosting a number of international mailing lists, for quite some time
without problem.  Of course, it has the advantage of being palindromic
so that big-endian lookups would not lose.  The name, which predates my
tenure here, is part of a whimsically-named cluster that includes
arpa.bio.net, org.bio.net, us.bio.net, mil.bio.net, com.bio.net, and
edu.bio.net, all purposely designed to drive nameservers nuts.
However, only net.bio.net has mail service (the rest are staff
workstations), and it is being renamed shortly anyhow.

--
Michael C. Berch  
mcb@presto.ig.com / uunet!presto.ig.com!mcb / ames!bionet!mcb

